## Migration: `Thread.Abort` → Cooperative Cancellation (.NET 8)

### Pattern Identified: **Timeout Enforcement**

Your code uses `Thread.Abort()` to kill a thread exceeding a time limit. In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is gone (`SYSLIB0006`).

### The Key Paradigm Shift

**.NET Framework (preemptive):** The runtime forcibly injects `ThreadAbortException` into the thread — the work code doesn't need to cooperate.

**.NET 8 (cooperative):** The work code **must voluntarily check** for cancellation. If it never checks, it never stops.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // CancellationTokenSource is IDisposable — always wrap in using
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException when the
            // token fires, even if Task.Run's body doesn't check it.
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

If you can make callers `async`, prefer the cleaner version:

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await Task.Run(work, cts.Token)
                             .WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

---

### What Was Removed and Why

| .NET Framework API | Replacement | Why |
|-|-|-|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` (via timeout) | `Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | `ThreadAbortException` is never thrown |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed entirely | No abort to reset |
| `new Thread(…)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(…)` | Simpler, uses thread pool |

---

### ⚠️ Critical Pitfall: Cooperative Cancellation Doesn't Kill Runaway Work

This is the **biggest difference** from .NET Framework. With `Thread.Abort`, the work was forcibly terminated. With cooperative cancellation, `Task.WaitAsync` lets your **caller** stop waiting, but **the work delegate keeps running** on a thread-pool thread until it finishes on its own.

If `work` is a tight CPU loop that never checks cancellation, it will run to completion in the background.

**If you control the work**, pass the token through and check it:

```csharp
// Caller
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => ProcessItems(items, cts.Token),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// Work that cooperates
T ProcessItems(List<Item> items, CancellationToken token)
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return BuildResult();
}
```

**If you don't control the work** (third-party code, native call), the only true equivalent to `Thread.Abort` is running it in a **separate process** and calling `Process.Kill()`:

```csharp
// Last resort — out-of-process execution
var process = Process.Start("WorkerApp.exe", args);
if (!process.WaitForExit(timeout))
{
    process.Kill(entireProcessTree: true);
    throw new TimeoutException("...");
}
```

---

### Other Pitfalls to Watch For

| Pitfall | Solution |
|-|-|
| Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource` | Always `using var cts = …` — leaking it leaks timers |
| `catch (OperationCanceledException)` swallowing real cancellation | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to only catch **your** timeout |
| Token not forwarded through the call chain | Every method in the chain must accept and pass `CancellationToken` |
| `Thread.Sleep` in work code doesn't respond to cancellation | Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or `await Task.Delay(ms, token)` |
